00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:43.530
to talk about, which is play.

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:46.100
I know you guys have been
in a class studying games.

00:04:46.100 --> 00:04:48.310
Have you talked much
about the word play?

00:04:48.310 --> 00:04:48.810
Good.

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:54.050
We are all in the
business of making games,

00:04:54.050 --> 00:04:56.180
and yet we don't stop
much to think about play.

00:04:56.180 --> 00:05:00.752
But play is not something that
was invented with the Atari.

00:05:00.752 --> 00:05:02.710
People have been playing
games for a long time.

00:05:02.710 --> 00:05:05.850
The oldest known game
implements are older

00:05:05.850 --> 00:05:07.810
than the oldest known writing.

00:05:11.104 --> 00:05:13.020
I don't know how many
of you know art history,

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:14.810
but this is the
late 16th century

00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:17.480
in what's now Belgium,
the low countries--

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.140
Flanders in those days.

00:05:20.140 --> 00:05:23.150
The great genre
painter Pieter Bruegel,

00:05:23.150 --> 00:05:26.880
who did a painting called
Children's Games, in which he

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:29.830
documented over 100
games that scholars have

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:31.695
been able to identify
as real games that

00:05:31.695 --> 00:05:32.820
were played at that time.

00:05:32.820 --> 00:05:38.100
And if you think about
it, at that point

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.820
there wasn't really much of
a thing called childhood.

00:05:40.820 --> 00:05:43.010
That by the age of 11
or 12, you were probably

00:05:43.010 --> 00:05:46.200
working in the family
business, whatever it was.

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:50.210
You were expected to take
on adult responsibilities.

00:05:50.210 --> 00:05:53.926
And yet clearly, play was still
a huge part of their lives.

00:05:53.926 --> 00:05:55.300
Now, this is a
fanciful painting.

00:05:55.300 --> 00:05:59.210
He was not trying to
be realistic here.

00:05:59.210 --> 00:06:04.580
But the point was play was a
huge part of their lives then.

00:06:04.580 --> 00:06:06.950
So we know that they
were playing back

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:08.890
in the 16th century.

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:11.460
We know they were
playing 6,000 years ago.

00:06:11.460 --> 00:06:15.650
We actually know that
our ancestors played too,

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:17.400
that other vertebrates play.

00:06:17.400 --> 00:06:20.870
In fact, Edwin Wilson has sort
of argued that ants play too,

00:06:20.870 --> 00:06:24.752
but let's just stick to
vertebrates for a minute.

00:06:24.752 --> 00:06:27.580
When mountain goats play--
there's a alpine mountain

00:06:27.580 --> 00:06:30.130
goat-- they play
by-- and by the way,

00:06:30.130 --> 00:06:32.470
let me just say quickly
from my definition,

00:06:32.470 --> 00:06:35.040
play is the stuff
you do when you don't

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:36.500
have to do something else.

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:38.040
You don't have to get food.

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:41.840
You don't have to evade
capture, or protect your young,

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:44.667
or procreate, or find shelter.

00:06:44.667 --> 00:06:47.000
When you don't have to do all
that stuff-- some of which

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.070
you do playfully, by
the way-- but when

00:06:49.070 --> 00:06:52.140
you don't have to do that
stuff and you're on your own,

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:54.070
you play.

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:56.740
And so mountain goats
play by actually chasing

00:06:56.740 --> 00:06:59.270
each other around the mountains
and jumping from cliff

00:06:59.270 --> 00:07:00.752
to cliff, ledge to ledge.

00:07:00.752 --> 00:07:02.210
And they do it in
spite of the fact

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:03.751
that mountain goats
will occasionally

00:07:03.751 --> 00:07:05.380
fall to their deaths.

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:07.120
And if we know anything
about evolution,

00:07:07.120 --> 00:07:10.430
we know the behaviors that lead
to the deaths of individuals

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:13.030
are behaviors that are
more likely to die out,

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:17.190
unless there is some
advantage to the behavior that

00:07:17.190 --> 00:07:19.170
outweighs the risk.

00:07:19.170 --> 00:07:21.010
And it would easy
to assume from this

00:07:21.010 --> 00:07:22.510
that mountain goats
are learning how

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:26.370
to do the things they need
to do, like jump and land

00:07:26.370 --> 00:07:27.542
on precarious ledges.

00:07:27.542 --> 00:07:29.750
That that's what they're
learning through their play.

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:32.330
We might extend
that thinking when

00:07:32.330 --> 00:07:34.470
we look at an image like this.

00:07:34.470 --> 00:07:37.940
By the way, you can find images
like this on the internet.

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:43.710
Anyway, so we've all seen
images of cats or puppies

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:46.355
fighting, playing at games that
look like fighting or hunting.

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:53.460
And if we take that example
and the example of the mountain

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:58.290
goats, it's easy to conclude
that play is about rote memory.

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:05.360
It's about learning to do
things through repetition.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:09.390
But they've done a study
where they prevented kittens

00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:11.550
from the opportunity to
play while they grow up,

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:12.950
play with other cats.

00:08:12.950 --> 00:08:16.665
And it turns out they learn
how to hunt just fine.

00:08:16.665 --> 00:08:18.040
What they don't
know how to do is

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:20.172
how to interact with
other cats or make

00:08:20.172 --> 00:08:21.380
other more complex decisions.

00:08:24.987 --> 00:08:27.070
What I'm going to argue
is play is about something

00:08:27.070 --> 00:08:32.450
far more involved that just sort
of rote memory and repetition.

00:08:32.450 --> 00:08:35.059
Last animal example.

00:08:35.059 --> 00:08:37.799
They did a study where they
gave an otter a fish every time

00:08:37.799 --> 00:08:39.270
it swam through a hoop.

00:08:39.270 --> 00:08:42.230
Now, if you think about
what an otter's needs are,

00:08:42.230 --> 00:08:45.090
that otter was rich
beyond its wildest dreams.

00:08:45.090 --> 00:08:46.880
Everything it needed
was right there just

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:48.270
by swimming through the hoop.

00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:51.587
So did the otter retire as we
might do if all our needs were

00:08:51.587 --> 00:08:52.170
taken care of?

00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:54.470
No, it started swimming
through the hoop upside down,

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:55.960
backwards.

00:08:55.960 --> 00:08:58.310
Playing with a hoop with
its way of exploring

00:08:58.310 --> 00:09:00.736
how the world worked.

00:09:00.736 --> 00:09:02.610
The otters-- I assume
there's more than one--

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:05.694
the otters knew that swimming
through a hoop got fish.

00:09:05.694 --> 00:09:07.610
They wanted to find out
what else it could do.

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:14.360
And again, this is when
survival is no longer an issue.

00:09:14.360 --> 00:09:18.170
So play is really the way in
which we explore the world.

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:20.300
Just looking at these
images of children,

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:23.430
there are four different
continents here,

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:25.580
four very different
kinds of games.

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:28.716
But I'd argue the affect
is the same in all of them,

00:09:28.716 --> 00:09:30.340
and that what's going
on in all of them

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:34.710
is the same thing, that
the kids in these pictures

00:09:34.710 --> 00:09:37.410
are really constructing their
understanding of the world

00:09:37.410 --> 00:09:39.920
through play.

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:42.820
What I want to argue is
that through play, we

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:47.850
begin to build the kinds
of conceptual structures

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:50.910
that we are going to then
engage with more formally

00:09:50.910 --> 00:09:52.710
in other spheres of life.

00:09:52.710 --> 00:09:56.040
And I could argue that
it's only for children,

00:09:56.040 --> 00:09:58.611
but I'm going to
argue further that it

00:09:58.611 --> 00:09:59.760
doesn't stop in childhood.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:01.635
But sticking with
childhood for just a moment

00:10:01.635 --> 00:10:04.510
and using my own
personal example.

00:10:04.510 --> 00:10:08.355
I loved playing with
blocks when I was a kid.

00:10:08.355 --> 00:10:09.730
And this is all
pre-kindergarten.

00:10:09.730 --> 00:10:11.870
I can remember the
pleasure of discovering

00:10:11.870 --> 00:10:14.940
that two square blocks
were the same size as one

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:17.580
rectangular block, and
two rectangular blocks

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:19.470
were the same size
as one big block.

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:22.590
And the kicker was that
that was equal to four

00:10:22.590 --> 00:10:25.580
of the little square blocks, and
that those relationships could

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:27.236
then be replicated elsewhere.

00:10:27.236 --> 00:10:29.360
That that was a pattern
that I could find elsewhere

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:30.120
in the world.

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:33.980
And so pre-kindergarten
now, what I am really doing

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:40.640
is developing a primitive,
but I would say robust sense

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:43.380
that math is the way we
actually model the world.

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:46.100
That we can actually model
the world mathematically.

00:10:46.100 --> 00:10:49.330
Now obviously, as four-year-old,
me couldn't have said that.

00:10:49.330 --> 00:10:52.900
Four-year-old me couldn't even
necessarily answer 2 plus 2

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:54.400
equals.

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:56.700
But four-year-old me knew
something far more robust.

00:10:56.700 --> 00:10:59.640
I was starting to
really understand

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:02.110
that the world could be
described mathematically,

00:11:02.110 --> 00:11:04.529
and that that was why
I was primed to be

00:11:04.529 --> 00:11:05.820
a relatively good math student.

00:11:08.890 --> 00:11:12.557
The challenge, though, is that I
just played with blocks the way

00:11:12.557 --> 00:11:13.640
I chose to play with them.

00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:14.320
No one made me.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:17.130
In fact, if you'd sat me
down and say play with blocks

00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:20.150
and discover what you can about
numbers, I might have refused

00:11:20.150 --> 00:11:21.840
and age four.

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:24.830
Players' motivations are
entirely intrinsic and personal

00:11:24.830 --> 00:11:26.600
in all play.

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:28.749
You cannot make somebody play.

00:11:28.749 --> 00:11:31.040
I think it's helpful to think
about it as if there were

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:34.300
four freedoms present in play.

00:11:34.300 --> 00:11:37.230
Freedom to experiment.

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:38.990
I thought I had
revised the slides.

00:11:38.990 --> 00:11:40.240
I really sort of revised that.

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:45.617
I think it's better say freedom
to explore is the better word.

00:11:45.617 --> 00:11:47.200
But what I was doing
with those blocks

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:49.520
was seeing things about
the blocks that were not--

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:51.139
the package showed
pictures of things

00:11:51.139 --> 00:11:52.930
you could build with
the blocks, but that's

00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:54.120
not what I was doing.

00:11:54.120 --> 00:11:56.160
I was sort of exploring
properties of the blocks

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:59.520
that no one was
telling me to look for.

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:01.470
Freedom to fail.

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:03.830
If you played with
blocks, you probably

00:12:03.830 --> 00:12:05.850
built a tower that
eventually fell down,

00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:08.711
and you probably learned a lot
from the tower falling down.

00:12:08.711 --> 00:12:10.460
You probably, in fact,
persisted at trying

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:11.585
to get the tower to stand up.

00:12:11.585 --> 00:12:13.920
And along the way, you were
learning all sorts of stuff

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:16.610
about mechanics and physics.

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:19.160
Freedom of identity.

00:12:19.160 --> 00:12:21.980
If you think about
doll play for a minute,

00:12:21.980 --> 00:12:26.290
a kid in the floor of
their room acting out

00:12:26.290 --> 00:12:29.760
conflict between two dolls,
or stuffed animals, or action

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:33.480
figures is really exploring all
the roles in their own family,

00:12:33.480 --> 00:12:35.070
in their world.

00:12:35.070 --> 00:12:37.450
A kid who plays at Luke
Skywalker versus Darth

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:40.280
Vader is really figuring
out what part of him

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:42.690
or herself is Luke
Skywalker and what part

00:12:42.690 --> 00:12:46.670
is Darth Vader, because we think
we have both of them in us.

00:12:46.670 --> 00:12:48.700
And that's what we
explore through play.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:52.620
In less than a week, on
Friday, a fair number of you

00:12:52.620 --> 00:12:55.970
are going to engage in identity
play at a fairly large scale,

00:12:55.970 --> 00:12:58.630
so it's not just
a childhood thing.

00:12:58.630 --> 00:13:02.400
I mean, I'm talking about
Halloween, obviously.

00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:04.940
And anyone who's ever
played World of Warcraft

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:09.780
or any number of games knows
that in fact, through games,

00:13:09.780 --> 00:13:12.530
we play with our
identity over time.

00:13:12.530 --> 00:13:15.230
Finally, freedom of
effort is the freedom

00:13:15.230 --> 00:13:18.460
to really play hard
or play relaxed.

00:13:18.460 --> 00:13:20.490
You cannot make
somebody play hard.

00:13:20.490 --> 00:13:23.030
And if you watched
the pattern of play,

00:13:23.030 --> 00:13:25.230
people will play intensely.

00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:26.802
They will suddenly ease up.

00:13:26.802 --> 00:13:28.760
Again, stick to World of
Warcraft for a minute,

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:29.926
sometimes you want to grind.

00:13:29.926 --> 00:13:33.110
You just want to do the
mindless stuff for a while.

00:13:33.110 --> 00:13:36.010
And sometimes you want to
enter into an intense battle.

00:13:36.010 --> 00:13:37.070
They both happen.

00:13:37.070 --> 00:13:39.179
So here's the challenge for us.

00:13:39.179 --> 00:13:40.720
The player's
motivations are entirely

00:13:40.720 --> 00:13:44.670
intrinsic and personal,
as I've already said.

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:47.500
And I'm also arguing
that obviously, learning

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:48.930
is happening through play.

00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:50.690
But how do we channel
play into learning

00:13:50.690 --> 00:13:52.440
while still allowing
for its fundamentally

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:54.644
open-ended nature?

00:13:54.644 --> 00:13:56.060
So if you, as Rick
said, are going

00:13:56.060 --> 00:14:00.010
to be making games in
which you want to-- well,

00:14:00.010 --> 00:14:04.520
I hope you're thinking about
real learning rather than just

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:05.900
conveying information.

00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:07.300
And I'll get to
that in a minute.

00:14:07.300 --> 00:14:10.200
But whatever it is you're
doing, theoretically you

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:12.240
want to make a good
game, they still

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:14.842
have to have the
freedom to play.

00:14:14.842 --> 00:14:16.300
You don't have a
game without play.

00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:18.040
You can have something that
has the structure of a game

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:19.220
without play, but
it won't really

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:20.770
be a game if
they're not playing.

00:14:20.770 --> 00:14:23.520
But anyway, so that's
where games come in.

00:14:23.520 --> 00:14:27.520
That's how we can channel
learning sometimes

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:28.730
while still being open ended.

00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:32.215
And just to use the most absurd
example, think about golf.

00:14:32.215 --> 00:14:36.900
It was Bernard Suits who
originally used this example.

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:39.220
But in golf, you're
hitting a very small ball

00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:41.770
with a very long stick.

00:14:41.770 --> 00:14:43.920
Anyone golf here?

00:14:43.920 --> 00:14:47.850
Yeah, that's what the normal
percentage is in a class.

00:14:47.850 --> 00:14:48.895
But it's hard, right ?

00:14:48.895 --> 00:14:50.520
The first time you
swung the golf club,

00:14:50.520 --> 00:14:53.330
you might have missed
the ball entirely, right?

00:14:53.330 --> 00:14:54.639
Yeah.

00:14:54.639 --> 00:14:56.930
Sometimes even when you start
connecting with the ball,

00:14:56.930 --> 00:14:58.540
it goes the wrong direction.

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:00.421
It goes 10 feet, 20 feet.

00:15:00.421 --> 00:15:02.170
When you can finally
hit it some distance,

00:15:02.170 --> 00:15:04.550
it goes into the water,
it goes into the woods.

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:07.880
It costs $2.50 every
time you lose a ball.

00:15:07.880 --> 00:15:10.390
If your goal, after all, is
to get the ball in the hole,

00:15:10.390 --> 00:15:12.723
why don't you just pick it
up, and walk to the other end

00:15:12.723 --> 00:15:13.860
of course, and drop it in?

00:15:13.860 --> 00:15:15.360
The golf game would
go much quicker.

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:16.640
You'd never lose a ball.

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:19.580
You have a lot more success.

00:15:19.580 --> 00:15:22.380
But no one chooses to
play golf that way.

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:24.980
If you think about
it, people choose

00:15:24.980 --> 00:15:27.720
to play golf by moving
the ball to the hole

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:32.640
in the single
stupidest way possible.

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:34.540
And as Bernard Suits
said in this context,

00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:36.130
games are really
about overcoming

00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:38.200
unnecessary obstacles.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:41.410
And unnecessary is critical
here because every game

00:15:41.410 --> 00:15:43.710
is, by definition, unnecessary.

00:15:43.710 --> 00:15:46.810
If you're really
playing, it's voluntary.

00:15:46.810 --> 00:15:48.470
It's not required.

00:15:48.470 --> 00:15:50.490
Your survival does
not depend on it.

00:15:50.490 --> 00:15:53.274
So by definition, every
game is unnecessary,

00:15:53.274 --> 00:15:55.690
and therefore the obstacles
in every game are unnecessary.

00:15:55.690 --> 00:15:58.520
And the game is the
voluntary overcoming

00:15:58.520 --> 00:15:59.850
of unnecessary obstacles.

00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:01.450
So why do we do it?

00:16:01.450 --> 00:16:03.234
Why would we do all that?

00:16:03.234 --> 00:16:04.650
Well, in games we
willingly submit

00:16:04.650 --> 00:16:06.700
to arbitrary rules
and structures

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:09.740
in pursuit of mastery because
that's what's going on in golf.

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:10.370
Even in golf.

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:17.140
You think it's hard, and yet
even though you missed the golf

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:19.515
ball the first time, you
think, I think I can hit it.

00:16:19.515 --> 00:16:20.890
And then eventually
you do hit it

00:16:20.890 --> 00:16:22.598
and you say, I think
I can hit it further

00:16:22.598 --> 00:16:24.440
and I think I can
hit it straighter.

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:26.739
And in fact, the game
gives you feedback.

00:16:26.739 --> 00:16:28.530
The game is continually
giving you feedback

00:16:28.530 --> 00:16:31.780
as to how you're doing.

00:16:31.780 --> 00:16:36.170
No matter how
ridiculously hard golf is,

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:38.555
you set for yourself
proximal goals.

00:16:38.555 --> 00:16:41.370
I'm going to hit a little
straighter, a little further.

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:43.200
And the game lets you do that.

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:44.720
No one runs out
into the golf course

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:48.270
and says, stop, you didn't
hit the ball far enough,

00:16:48.270 --> 00:16:52.735
or yells at you and says, hit
it further, further, right?

00:16:52.735 --> 00:16:54.920
They let you
playfully explore what

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:56.530
you can do with that golf ball.

00:16:56.530 --> 00:16:58.290
And you keep saying
I'm getting better,

00:16:58.290 --> 00:17:00.230
and so you keep playing golf.

00:17:00.230 --> 00:17:03.370
And that's true with every game.

00:17:03.370 --> 00:17:06.290
And I'll talk about a couple
other examples going forward

00:17:06.290 --> 00:17:07.140
about that.

00:17:07.140 --> 00:17:10.990
So games give you proximal goals
which seem worth achieving,

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:13.250
but only if you can
continue to be playful.

00:17:13.250 --> 00:17:15.060
And that's I think
the thing we sometimes

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:18.200
lose sight of when we're making
games is the playfulness.

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:19.789
We remember the goal.

00:17:19.789 --> 00:17:21.830
We remember that there's
an outcome that we want.

00:17:21.830 --> 00:17:25.160
And we remember that we want the
player to get to that outcome.

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:27.980
But we forget about
playfulness, which means we

00:17:27.980 --> 00:17:29.510
either make a game
that's too easy.

00:17:29.510 --> 00:17:31.295
We lead them right
to the outcome.

00:17:31.295 --> 00:17:33.920
That's like picking up the ball
, and walking to the other end,

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:35.086
and dropping it in the hole.

00:17:35.086 --> 00:17:37.290
And a lot of games do that.

00:17:37.290 --> 00:17:41.399
Or we just figure I'm going
to make it really hard.

00:17:41.399 --> 00:17:43.190
I don't care whether
they enjoy themselves.

00:17:43.190 --> 00:17:44.669
They're going to get there.

00:17:44.669 --> 00:17:45.710
And of course they don't.

00:17:45.710 --> 00:17:46.270
They quit.

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:55.710
It's one thing to
define a challenge.

00:17:55.710 --> 00:17:57.130
That's important.

00:17:57.130 --> 00:18:00.030
The real art in it is
defining a proximal challenge,

00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:01.244
one that people can reach.

00:18:01.244 --> 00:18:03.410
And I would argue that if
you're talking about games

00:18:03.410 --> 00:18:05.450
in which you want to
convey information

00:18:05.450 --> 00:18:08.480
or you want people to learn
something, all of that

00:18:08.480 --> 00:18:09.212
has to hold true.

00:18:09.212 --> 00:18:10.920
And in fact, the other
thing I'm arguing,

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:13.260
obviously, is that at in every
game, people are learning.

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:14.801
That the reason you
like playing golf

00:18:14.801 --> 00:18:16.530
is because you're learning.

00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:19.110
And Raph Koster sets
this out really well

00:18:19.110 --> 00:18:21.650
in the Theory of Fun,
the book A Theory of Fun.

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:23.590
But that basically, the
fundamental pleasure

00:18:23.590 --> 00:18:25.690
of gameplay is
learning, is learning

00:18:25.690 --> 00:18:28.706
to master the game,
which means in a sense,

00:18:28.706 --> 00:18:30.080
if you're doing
a game and you've

00:18:30.080 --> 00:18:35.180
got some goal for some learning
to happen, all you've got to do

00:18:35.180 --> 00:18:37.320
is make that learning
interesting and worth

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:43.410
achieving by giving people
the right set of goals

00:18:43.410 --> 00:18:46.190
to work toward it.

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:48.880
So I keep talking kind of
interchangeably between play

00:18:48.880 --> 00:18:49.470
and learning.

00:18:49.470 --> 00:18:54.120
And yet the four freedoms
of play, which I'm arguing

00:18:54.120 --> 00:18:56.290
are the four
freedoms of learning,

00:18:56.290 --> 00:18:58.567
are not the four
freedoms of school.

00:18:58.567 --> 00:19:01.150
If you think about school, and
I'm not talking about MIT right

00:19:01.150 --> 00:19:04.560
now, if you think about your
own high school experience--

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:08.401
high school is particularly
bad-- what kind of freedom

00:19:08.401 --> 00:19:08.900
is there?

00:19:08.900 --> 00:19:09.800
Freedom to fail?

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:11.150
Not so much.

00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:12.030
Freedom to explore?

00:19:12.030 --> 00:19:17.344
Well, I mean, even a
high school science lab,

00:19:17.344 --> 00:19:19.760
everyone is expecting to get
the same results by following

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:22.690
the exact same procedure, right?

00:19:22.690 --> 00:19:26.201
And that's the most experimental
you ever get in school.

00:19:26.201 --> 00:19:28.450
Certainly no freedom of
effort or freedom of identity.

00:19:28.450 --> 00:19:29.930
You sit in your
same seat every day

00:19:29.930 --> 00:19:34.482
and you're expected to
behave the exact same way.

00:19:34.482 --> 00:19:36.190
And you're expected
to work equally hard.

00:19:36.190 --> 00:19:40.460
You can't come in and say I
don't feel like working today.

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:42.390
So there's very
little play in school,

00:19:42.390 --> 00:19:43.980
at least as it's
currently embodied.

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:45.940
And this is why I
mention school here,

00:19:45.940 --> 00:19:49.985
is because I think
one of the challenges

00:19:49.985 --> 00:19:52.360
if you're an MIT student is
that you were probably pretty

00:19:52.360 --> 00:19:54.940
good at the game of school.

00:19:54.940 --> 00:19:57.346
You probably did what
was required of you.

00:19:57.346 --> 00:20:00.600
You probably didn't
necessarily recognize

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:03.100
that doing the things that
school required of you

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:04.835
is not when you were
actually learning,

00:20:04.835 --> 00:20:06.670
that that was just
playing the game.

00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:09.725
That the learning was
more self-motivated

00:20:09.725 --> 00:20:11.500
and more self-directed.

00:20:11.500 --> 00:20:13.920
And so frequently people,
when they turn around

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:16.500
and try to make anything
to do with learning,

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:20.130
whether it's a game, or write
a book, or create a curriculum,

00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:23.880
they replicate everything
that's bad about school.

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:28.010
And the reason I don't like to
say I make educational games

00:20:28.010 --> 00:20:30.175
is because when you think
of educational games,

00:20:30.175 --> 00:20:32.300
you think of all the bad
games that have replicated

00:20:32.300 --> 00:20:34.220
what's bad about school.

00:20:34.220 --> 00:20:38.070
Games that have largely taken
the dead carcass of a game

00:20:38.070 --> 00:20:41.090
and stuffed it full
of academic content.

00:20:41.090 --> 00:20:44.450
So you're going
to shoot at aliens

00:20:44.450 --> 00:20:47.360
and you're going to
memorize your times table.

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:50.635
Now, what aliens have to do
with times tables, I don't know.

00:20:50.635 --> 00:20:52.760
Any I'd even argue that
memorizing your times table

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:54.730
is of questionable value.

00:20:54.730 --> 00:20:57.560
There may be a place
for it, but it's

00:20:57.560 --> 00:21:01.620
certainly not what being good
at math is about, fundamentally.

00:21:01.620 --> 00:21:04.480
And too often,
games for learning

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:07.875
end up being about simply
I'm going to feed you content

00:21:07.875 --> 00:21:09.250
that would be
boring in a lecture

00:21:09.250 --> 00:21:10.445
or boring in a textbook.

00:21:10.445 --> 00:21:11.070
And guess what?

00:21:11.070 --> 00:21:12.820
It's going to be just
as boring in a game.

00:21:12.820 --> 00:21:14.236
The only difference
is we're going

00:21:14.236 --> 00:21:16.970
to surround it with things that
we think you think are fun,

00:21:16.970 --> 00:21:18.410
like shooting at aliens.

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:22.180
So it sort of
translates into people

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:23.770
thinking that what
the world needs

00:21:23.770 --> 00:21:26.535
is something like
Grand Theft Calculus.

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:32.464
But in fact, without
playfulness, a game

00:21:32.464 --> 00:21:33.880
is just going
through the motions.

00:21:33.880 --> 00:21:36.180
It's just gym class.

00:21:36.180 --> 00:21:38.870
Volleyball in gym is not
the same as volleyball

00:21:38.870 --> 00:21:41.260
at the beach, and there's
a reason for that.

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:46.601
And even smart MIT
kids making games

00:21:46.601 --> 00:21:48.600
when they think there's
learning involved end up

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:52.054
reverting to gym
class, to just I'm

00:21:52.054 --> 00:21:54.220
going to make you play this
game to learn this stuff

00:21:54.220 --> 00:21:56.560
you don't want to learn.

00:21:56.560 --> 00:21:58.012
Just to talk about
the difference

00:21:58.012 --> 00:22:00.220
between a good learning game
and a bad learning game,

00:22:00.220 --> 00:22:02.220
let's talk about difference
between spelling bee

00:22:02.220 --> 00:22:04.030
and Scrabble.

00:22:04.030 --> 00:22:10.470
In a spelling bee, most of
us, when we do a spelling bee,

00:22:10.470 --> 00:22:11.610
are nervous.

00:22:11.610 --> 00:22:12.890
Our palms are sweating.

00:22:12.890 --> 00:22:15.765
We think we're going to fail.

00:22:15.765 --> 00:22:17.140
Eventually the
moment comes where

00:22:17.140 --> 00:22:18.223
they say no, you're wrong.

00:22:18.223 --> 00:22:18.790
Sit down.

00:22:18.790 --> 00:22:21.800
You're probably relieved.

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:24.867
When they say, you're wrong,
sit down, nobody says to you,

00:22:24.867 --> 00:22:27.200
well, that was interesting
that you spelled it that way,

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:30.080
or I can understand why you
might have chosen to spell it

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:31.920
that way, because
it rhymes with-- no.

00:22:31.920 --> 00:22:33.990
They just say you're
wrong, sit down.

00:22:33.990 --> 00:22:35.220
And that's the end of it.

00:22:35.220 --> 00:22:37.940
The end of a spelling bee, one
person feels good, the winner.

00:22:37.940 --> 00:22:40.477
Maybe the kid who comes
in second feels OK.

00:22:40.477 --> 00:22:42.310
Everyone else is relieved
because they don't

00:22:42.310 --> 00:22:44.880
have to do spelling anymore.

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:48.850
And I first coined this analogy
thinking about bad games.

00:22:48.850 --> 00:22:51.716
But I later came to
realize that it's bigger

00:22:51.716 --> 00:22:53.340
than that, because
if you think about--

00:22:53.340 --> 00:22:55.089
so I don't know how
many of you know this,

00:22:55.089 --> 00:22:56.570
but 7% of the
population in the US

00:22:56.570 --> 00:22:58.070
graduates high
school saying they're

00:22:58.070 --> 00:23:02.720
good at math, which means
we take an hour a day

00:23:02.720 --> 00:23:06.340
for 12 years teaching
93% of the population

00:23:06.340 --> 00:23:08.650
that they're not good at math.

00:23:08.650 --> 00:23:11.180
We would be doing them all a
big favor by in kindergarten,

00:23:11.180 --> 00:23:14.860
saying you're not going to do
math and just leave it at that.

00:23:14.860 --> 00:23:16.540
Or better yet, we
could figure out ways

00:23:16.540 --> 00:23:17.956
that teaching
method that actually

00:23:17.956 --> 00:23:20.750
were meaningful and relevant to
people, rather than making them

00:23:20.750 --> 00:23:22.250
feel like they're
not good at math.

00:23:25.350 --> 00:23:26.661
So that's a bad game.

00:23:26.661 --> 00:23:29.160
And so what I'm really arguing
is that school is a bad game.

00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:32.050
School is a game in
which we reward people

00:23:32.050 --> 00:23:33.656
for learning how
to play at school.

00:23:33.656 --> 00:23:35.280
Sometimes they're
smart at some things.

00:23:35.280 --> 00:23:36.946
I'm not saying that
there aren't people.

00:23:36.946 --> 00:23:39.580
But largely our goal
is to weed people out.

00:23:39.580 --> 00:23:42.250
And we filter some
people into some fields

00:23:42.250 --> 00:23:43.460
because they seem good at it.

00:23:43.460 --> 00:23:45.459
For everyone else, we're
sort of convincing them

00:23:45.459 --> 00:23:47.520
that they-- whew, I don't
have to study anymore.

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:48.394
I'm done with school.

00:23:48.394 --> 00:23:50.060
I never have to
learn anything again.

00:23:50.060 --> 00:23:53.520
That's the way most people
end up leaving school.

00:23:53.520 --> 00:23:55.350
Scrabble, you sit down.

00:23:55.350 --> 00:23:56.189
You got your board.

00:23:56.189 --> 00:23:56.980
You got your tiles.

00:23:56.980 --> 00:23:58.396
You're moving
around all the time.

00:23:58.396 --> 00:24:01.210
You're being creative even
in the downtime just thinking

00:24:01.210 --> 00:24:02.600
about all the words you know.

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:04.310
If you never win a
game of Scrabble,

00:24:04.310 --> 00:24:07.020
you have all sorts of
other proximal goals,

00:24:07.020 --> 00:24:09.675
like getting a 50-point word,
or getting a triple word score,

00:24:09.675 --> 00:24:11.540
or getting the highest
score you ever got.

00:24:11.540 --> 00:24:15.890
Just like golf, it gives
you lots of feedback.

00:24:15.890 --> 00:24:17.710
By the way, most
people who play golf,

00:24:17.710 --> 00:24:19.090
they're not in a tournament.

00:24:19.090 --> 00:24:21.820
They're not playing
to win a game.

00:24:21.820 --> 00:24:23.104
They made their own game.

00:24:23.104 --> 00:24:25.520
Maybe I'm going to get a lower
score than I got last time,

00:24:25.520 --> 00:24:27.170
or maybe I'm going to get at a
lower score than the person I'm

00:24:27.170 --> 00:24:27.840
playing with.

00:24:27.840 --> 00:24:29.829
Well, at Scrabble,
it's the same thing.

00:24:29.829 --> 00:24:32.370
So you're continually setting
your own goals within the game.

00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:34.890
The game has goals.

00:24:34.890 --> 00:24:37.050
It has something called victory.

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:38.920
And we all may aspire
to that victory,

00:24:38.920 --> 00:24:41.750
but we have lots of other
ways of measuring ourselves

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:43.360
that are not about victory.

00:24:43.360 --> 00:24:46.380
And every player makes up
their own game within Scrabble,

00:24:46.380 --> 00:24:48.820
and golf, and any good game.

00:24:48.820 --> 00:24:51.340
We actually all play a different
game when we play a game,

00:24:51.340 --> 00:24:53.720
and that's not a
fault to the game.

00:24:53.720 --> 00:25:01.020
So one last thing I sort of want
to bring into the conversation

00:25:01.020 --> 00:25:04.832
as we think about
this is an expression.

00:25:04.832 --> 00:25:07.415
It dates back to around the same
time as the Bruegel painting.

00:25:07.415 --> 00:25:11.480
But in English, we first see the
expression all work and no play

00:25:11.480 --> 00:25:12.920
makes Jack a dull boy.

00:25:12.920 --> 00:25:15.140
And at first, your
first response

00:25:15.140 --> 00:25:16.680
is that's a good thing, right?

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:19.204
Yes, play is important.

00:25:19.204 --> 00:25:20.870
So it seems to be a
statement in support

00:25:20.870 --> 00:25:21.640
of what I've been saying.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:24.181
But the only trouble with it is
that it also sort of suggests

00:25:24.181 --> 00:25:26.080
that there is this dichotomy.

00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:27.620
There's work and there's play.

00:25:27.620 --> 00:25:29.470
And I may have sort
of suggested it

00:25:29.470 --> 00:25:31.136
by saying it's the
thing you do when you

00:25:31.136 --> 00:25:33.390
don't have to do anything else.

00:25:33.390 --> 00:25:35.290
But then I did
modify that by saying

00:25:35.290 --> 00:25:37.880
that you do some of these
other things playfully as well.

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:40.080
And in fact, when
we go into school,

00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:42.420
we think that there's
learning and there's play

00:25:42.420 --> 00:25:44.435
and they're different.

00:25:44.435 --> 00:25:46.810
But in fact, I'm going to go
quickly through those slides

00:25:46.810 --> 00:25:48.268
and just go up to
here and just say

00:25:48.268 --> 00:25:52.474
I think we really need to
think of it more like this.

00:25:52.474 --> 00:25:54.515
And we need to think about
situating things here.

00:25:58.970 --> 00:25:59.880
And fun, by the way.

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:01.640
Let me just be clear about fun.

00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:04.640
Fun is not giggles.

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:08.260
Fun doesn't even necessarily
require a smile on the face.

00:26:08.260 --> 00:26:10.490
If you think about yourself
playing a video game

00:26:10.490 --> 00:26:12.560
at age 11 or 12,
there were probably

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:15.580
moments where your
tongue was sticking out,

00:26:15.580 --> 00:26:16.960
and you're cross
eyed, and you're

00:26:16.960 --> 00:26:18.760
yelling at the screen,
that's not fair,

00:26:18.760 --> 00:26:20.330
and you threw your controller.

00:26:20.330 --> 00:26:23.890
And then you beat the game
and said, that was fun.

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:27.460
And Seymour Papert a retired
professor from the Media Lab,

00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:30.300
is the one who coined
the term hard fun.

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:32.270
And hard fun is not
a special category.

00:26:32.270 --> 00:26:37.110
I would argue that lots of fun
is hard fun, maybe most fun.

00:26:37.110 --> 00:26:41.720
Certainly most
games are hard fun,

00:26:41.720 --> 00:26:45.780
and that most good
learning is hard fun.

00:26:45.780 --> 00:26:49.490
The things you learn that
aren't fun, yes, there

00:26:49.490 --> 00:26:51.994
may be some value to
memorizing your times tables,

00:26:51.994 --> 00:26:53.660
but it doesn't make
you a mathematician.

00:26:53.660 --> 00:26:55.493
That's not where the
real learning happened.

00:26:59.010 --> 00:27:03.430
There's things you have to
memorize-- although I heard

00:27:03.430 --> 00:27:05.090
somewhere that a
10th grade biology

00:27:05.090 --> 00:27:07.340
student has to memorize
more words than a 10th grade

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:08.960
French student.

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:11.959
And if you think about it, how
many of us, other than those

00:27:11.959 --> 00:27:14.000
of us who go to biology,
ever use all those words

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:15.021
that we memorized about?

00:27:15.021 --> 00:27:15.520
None of it.

00:27:15.520 --> 00:27:19.470
So, I mean, I think too much
of our vision of learning

00:27:19.470 --> 00:27:22.980
is still based on memorizing
stuff that you then

00:27:22.980 --> 00:27:25.757
get tested on, rather
than building up

00:27:25.757 --> 00:27:27.340
cognitive structures
that you can then

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:29.910
work with through the rest
of your life, which is what

00:27:29.910 --> 00:27:32.310
we really want people to do.

00:27:32.310 --> 00:27:34.830
That's my point, because
I know you're doing

00:27:34.830 --> 00:27:36.700
this work with the Red Cross.

00:27:36.700 --> 00:27:40.500
You have information
you want to convey.

00:27:40.500 --> 00:27:42.500
I want to argue that if
the information you want

00:27:42.500 --> 00:27:44.730
to convey fits on a 3
by 5 card and people

00:27:44.730 --> 00:27:48.464
can carry it around
with them, then

00:27:48.464 --> 00:27:50.130
there's no point in
making a game of it.

00:27:54.450 --> 00:27:56.490
So just to do a
parallel example,

00:27:56.490 --> 00:28:04.281
I've done games for the working
poor, games where the goal is

00:28:04.281 --> 00:28:06.780
to explain to them that they
shouldn't take out payday loans

00:28:06.780 --> 00:28:08.817
or take on credit card debt.

00:28:08.817 --> 00:28:11.025
Well, in fact, you could
write that on a 3 by 5 card.

00:28:11.025 --> 00:28:12.700
If I handed it to
most people and said

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:14.533
don't take out a payday
loan, don't take out

00:28:14.533 --> 00:28:18.390
credit card debt, they would
nod, and smile, and agree.

00:28:18.390 --> 00:28:20.400
And then they would
go and do it when

00:28:20.400 --> 00:28:22.580
they were in extremis, anyway.

00:28:22.580 --> 00:28:24.660
They don't do it
blithely, but they do it.

00:28:24.660 --> 00:28:27.680
But my point is that the
understanding that you really

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:29.951
need is more subtle
and more complicated.

00:28:29.951 --> 00:28:32.450
You really want to give people
some functional understanding

00:28:32.450 --> 00:28:33.210
of something.

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:35.376
So when we did that game,
what we really tried to do

00:28:35.376 --> 00:28:38.340
is put people in the situations
in which they might otherwise

00:28:38.340 --> 00:28:41.065
get loans and help them see
what the alternatives were.

00:28:41.065 --> 00:28:44.360
That that was the important
learning, and helping them

00:28:44.360 --> 00:28:46.670
recognize those moments.

00:28:46.670 --> 00:28:49.720
The learning was sort of
helping them, and helping

00:28:49.720 --> 00:28:52.777
them feel empowered to be
able to make decisions.

00:28:52.777 --> 00:28:54.735
So we were doing lots of
stuff beyond conveying

00:28:54.735 --> 00:28:58.470
the information don't take
out of credit card debt.

00:28:58.470 --> 00:29:01.210
And so similarly, I think you're
doing games where you probably

00:29:01.210 --> 00:29:03.540
think you want to
convey information,

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:06.870
but that's all information
that could fit on a pamphlet,

00:29:06.870 --> 00:29:09.097
or on a 3 by 5 card,
and you probably really

00:29:09.097 --> 00:29:10.680
don't want to make
a game out of that.

00:29:10.680 --> 00:29:12.950
You probably really want
to make a game that's

00:29:12.950 --> 00:29:17.690
going to be about helping people
through some experience master

00:29:17.690 --> 00:29:19.670
something.

00:29:19.670 --> 00:29:22.490
And through their sense
of mastery, change them.

00:29:22.490 --> 00:29:25.600
So I think that's it
in a nutshell, what

00:29:25.600 --> 00:29:29.850
I want to say, and just use the
rest of the time for questions.

00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:32.117
And then you're to see
your paper projects

00:29:32.117 --> 00:29:32.950
with everybody else.

