00:34:52.840 --> 00:34:55.130
I think we freely make
the mistake of imagining

00:34:55.130 --> 00:34:57.315
a certain path for a
player on the win state,

00:34:57.315 --> 00:34:59.250
and we design the game
around that player,

00:34:59.250 --> 00:35:01.240
following the path
to the win state.

00:35:01.240 --> 00:35:03.570
And we forget to think
about all of the time

00:35:03.570 --> 00:35:05.520
that players are
likely to spend either

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:08.520
trying to break the game,
or play in different modes,

00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:10.204
or in fail state.

00:35:10.204 --> 00:35:12.370
I mean, one of the things
I encourage students to do

00:35:12.370 --> 00:35:14.786
is make sure that the failure
is the most interesting part

00:35:14.786 --> 00:35:17.490
of your game, because if your
game is at all challenging,

00:35:17.490 --> 00:35:21.270
people are going to be spending
a lot of time in failure mode.

00:35:21.270 --> 00:35:24.580
A, you want to reward
them and say that's OK.

00:35:24.580 --> 00:35:27.565
We're happy to see you here.

00:35:27.565 --> 00:35:29.940
And b, you want to make sure
that it remains entertaining

00:35:29.940 --> 00:35:33.900
while they're in failure
mode so they don't quit.

00:35:33.900 --> 00:35:35.900
Like I said, I think
it's an easy mistake

00:35:35.900 --> 00:35:38.170
to fixate on what's the
path to success look

00:35:38.170 --> 00:35:40.710
like, and not think about
what the whole gameplay

00:35:40.710 --> 00:35:42.940
experience is like.

00:35:42.940 --> 00:35:45.790
And that gets worse when
people have an agenda,

00:35:45.790 --> 00:35:49.200
like a game for the Red Cross.

00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:50.470
We really fall into that trap.

00:35:50.470 --> 00:35:53.270
And that's why so many
serious games seem

00:35:53.270 --> 00:35:58.030
so serious, and
earnest, and humorless,

00:35:58.030 --> 00:36:01.470
because all the
designer thought about

00:36:01.470 --> 00:36:04.670
was the player earnestly
achieving the goals

00:36:04.670 --> 00:36:07.174
that the designer set
out for the player,

00:36:07.174 --> 00:36:09.090
rather than thinking
about the player playing.

