00:49:08.650 --> 00:49:09.947
Forecast-Based Funding, right?

00:49:09.947 --> 00:49:10.530
AUDIENCE: Yep.

00:49:14.700 --> 00:49:16.840
Hi, we're
Forecast-Based Funding.

00:49:16.840 --> 00:49:19.930
The general idea
behind our concept

00:49:19.930 --> 00:49:21.960
is that planning
ahead for disasters

00:49:21.960 --> 00:49:23.840
is much better than
trying to react to them.

00:49:23.840 --> 00:49:26.615
So if you can have operating
procedures or ways of planning

00:49:26.615 --> 00:49:29.320
for them [INAUDIBLE]
afford that,

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:34.110
you can reduce loss of lives
in the event of disasters.

00:49:34.110 --> 00:49:36.240
We are actually
between two prototypes

00:49:36.240 --> 00:49:39.590
right now that we're testing
to try and get at the ideas.

00:49:39.590 --> 00:49:44.090
The first one is a sort
of higher-level city-based

00:49:44.090 --> 00:49:47.910
simulation of a city that's
at risk of disaster, which you

00:49:47.910 --> 00:49:50.035
then have to fortify,
[INAUDIBLE] train volunteers,

00:49:50.035 --> 00:49:53.200
or preparing for
upcoming disasters

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:56.466
in order to prevent too much
damage from happening to them.

00:49:56.466 --> 00:49:58.590
One of the problems that
we're seeing with the game

00:49:58.590 --> 00:50:01.810
is that's kind of abstract
and not as interactive

00:50:01.810 --> 00:50:03.270
for players to connect with.

00:50:03.270 --> 00:50:04.978
But they are getting
a good understanding

00:50:04.978 --> 00:50:07.218
of the idea of planning ahead.

00:50:07.218 --> 00:50:08.120
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:50:08.120 --> 00:50:09.780
And so to try and
address those issues,

00:50:09.780 --> 00:50:11.430
we have a second
prototype right now,

00:50:11.430 --> 00:50:16.840
which is about trying
to actually rescue

00:50:16.840 --> 00:50:18.570
people in a flooding city.

00:50:18.570 --> 00:50:21.320
And so that hits the other
end of the scale, where

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:25.200
the player is told ahead
of time this disaster

00:50:25.200 --> 00:50:28.320
was planned for versus this
disaster was not planned for,

00:50:28.320 --> 00:50:31.742
and the appropriate
effects for each.

00:50:31.742 --> 00:50:33.200
And then they have
to rescue people

00:50:33.200 --> 00:50:35.320
under those two
different conditions,

00:50:35.320 --> 00:50:37.220
and then they get
to directly compare

00:50:37.220 --> 00:50:42.240
what the experience of
is for acting in one

00:50:42.240 --> 00:50:44.190
circumstance versus the other.

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:45.815
AUDIENCE: Over the
next couple of days,

00:50:45.815 --> 00:50:49.235
we'll be looking at what we
learned from both of them

00:50:49.235 --> 00:50:51.560
and trying to either
combine them or pull out

00:50:51.560 --> 00:50:56.182
the parts that we thought were
really useful to [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:56.182 --> 00:50:58.174
PROFESSOR: [INAUDIBLE] on this?

00:50:58.174 --> 00:50:59.170
This was the hard one.

00:50:59.170 --> 00:50:59.668
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:50:59.668 --> 00:51:00.626
PROFESSOR: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:51:02.819 --> 00:51:04.860
AUDIENCE: I think it was
stated a couple of times

00:51:04.860 --> 00:51:07.720
that we should be looking at
people that are policymakers

00:51:07.720 --> 00:51:10.987
or donors in the sense of
sort of people who would be

00:51:10.987 --> 00:51:13.970
allocating funds from
governments or non-profits,

00:51:13.970 --> 00:51:15.261
things like that.

00:51:15.261 --> 00:51:17.510
Basically we make it appear
that this type of planning

00:51:17.510 --> 00:51:19.510
ahead is a good idea.

